[
  {
    "fnNumber": "1",
    "fnHTML": "<p>The first to equate <span lang='pi'>viññāṇa</span> <span lang='pi'>ani&shy;das&shy;sana</span> to nibbāna is, to my knowledge, <span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Falk 1943a'>Falk</span> 1943. But this and similar ideas are still very alive today.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "2",
    "fnHTML": "<p>E.g. <span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;1.2<span class='scsegments'>:5.2</span></span>, <span class='sclinktext'>AN&#8239;3.90<span class='scsegments'>:9.1–9.4</span></span>, <span class='sclinktext'>Snp&#8239;3.12<span class='scsegments'>:18.3–20.4</span></span>, <span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;8.9<span class='scsegments'>:5.4</span></span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "3",
    "fnHTML": "<p>E.g.  <span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;22.10<span class='scsegments'>:1.10–1.11</span></span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "4",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Analayo 2017a'>Anālayo 2017</span>, <span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Brahmali 2009a'>Brahmali</span>, <span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Sujato 2011a'>Sujato 2011a</span>, and <span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Sujato 2011b'>Sujato 2011b</span>, among others.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "5",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>DN&#8239;11<span class='scsegments'>:85.18</span></span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "6",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>MN&#8239;49<span class='scsegments'>:25.1</span></span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "7",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>AN&#8239;11.17<span class='scsegments'>:3.1–3.3</span></span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "8",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>DN&#8239;11<span class='scsegments'>:85.11–85.27</span></span> <span class='ptsref'>PTS: D I 223</span> ‘<span lang='pi'>Kattha</span> <span lang='pi'>āpo</span> <span lang='pi'>ca</span> <span lang='pi'>pathavī</span>, <span lang='pi'>tejo</span> <span lang='pi'>vāyo</span> <span lang='pi'>na</span> <span lang='pi'>gādhati</span>? <span lang='pi'>Kattha</span> <span lang='pi'>dīg&shy;hañ&shy;ca</span> <span lang='pi'>ras&shy;sañ&shy;ca</span>, <span lang='pi'>aṇuṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>thūlaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>sub&shy;hā&shy;su&shy;bhaṁ</span>; <span lang='pi'>Kattha</span> <span lang='pi'>nāmañca</span> <span lang='pi'>rūpañca</span>, <span lang='pi'>asesaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>up&shy;ar&shy;uj&shy;jha&shy;tī’ti</span>? <span lang='pi'>Tatra</span> <span lang='pi'>vey&shy;yāka&shy;ra&shy;ṇaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>bhavati</span>: ‘<span lang='pi'>Viñ&shy;ñāṇ&shy;aṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>ani&shy;das&shy;sanaṁ</span>, <span lang='pi'>anantaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>sabbato</span> <span lang='pi'>pabhaṁ</span>; <span lang='pi'>Ettha</span> <span lang='pi'>āpo</span> <span lang='pi'>ca</span> <span lang='pi'>pathavī</span>, <span lang='pi'>tejo</span> <span lang='pi'>vāyo</span> <span lang='pi'>na</span> <span lang='pi'>gādhati</span>. <span lang='pi'>Ettha</span> <span lang='pi'>dīg&shy;hañ&shy;ca</span> <span lang='pi'>ras&shy;sañ&shy;ca</span>, <span lang='pi'>aṇuṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>thūlaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>sub&shy;hā&shy;su&shy;bhaṁ</span>; <span lang='pi'>Ettha</span> <span lang='pi'>nāmañca</span> <span lang='pi'>rūpañca</span>, <span lang='pi'>asesaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>up&shy;ar&shy;uj&shy;jha&shy;ti</span>; <span lang='pi'>Viñ&shy;ñāṇ&shy;as&shy;sa</span> <span lang='pi'>ni&shy;ro&shy;dhe&shy;na</span>, <span lang='pi'>et&shy;thet&shy;aṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>up&shy;ar&shy;uj&shy;jha&shy;tī’ti</span>.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "9",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>Snp&#8239;4.11</span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "10",
    "fnHTML": "<p>E.g. <span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;28.6<span class='scsegments'>:1.3</span></span>: ‘<span lang='pi'>anantaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>viñ&shy;ñā&shy;ṇan’ti</span> <span lang='pi'>viñ&shy;ñā&shy;ṇañ&shy;cā&shy;ya&shy;ta&shy;naṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>upa&shy;sam&shy;paj&shy;ja</span> <span lang='pi'>vi&shy;ha&shy;rā&shy;ti</span>.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "11",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Warder 1991a'>Warder</span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "12",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>AN&#8239;5.23<span class='scsegments'>:2.1–2.6</span></span>: <span lang='pi'>Yato</span> <span lang='pi'>ca</span> <span lang='pi'>kho</span>, <span lang='pi'>bhik&shy;kha&shy;ve</span>, <span lang='pi'>cittaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>imehi</span> <span lang='pi'>pañcahi</span> <span lang='pi'>upak&shy;ki&shy;le&shy;se&shy;hi</span> <span lang='pi'>vi&shy;mut&shy;taṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>hoti</span> <em>[…]</em> <span lang='pi'>pab&shy;has&shy;sar&shy;añ&shy;ca</span>.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "13",
    "fnHTML": "<p>E.g. <span class='sclinktext'>MN&#8239;140<span class='scsegments'>:20.1–20.3</span></span> <span class='ptsref'>PTS: M III 243</span>, <span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;51.22<span class='scsegments'>:3.1–4.3</span></span>, <span class='sclinktext'>AN&#8239;3.102<span class='scsegments'>:1.6, 3.6</span></span>, <span class='sclinktext'>Thag&#8239;20.1<span class='scsegments'>:59.1–61.4</span></span>, <span class='sclinktext'>Dhp&#8239;387</span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "14",
    "fnHTML": "<p>E.g. <span class='sclinktext'>AN&#8239;9.31<span class='scsegments'>:1.7–1.8</span></span>: “For one who has attained the base of boundless space, the perception of form has ceased. For one who has attained the base of boundless consciousness, the perception present in the base of boundless space has ceased.”. C.f. <span class='sclinktext'>AN&#8239;10.6</span> where in a list of (gradual) cessation of perception the formless attainments follows the four elements, i.e. form.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "15",
    "fnHTML": "<p>Cf. e.g. Rhys Davids, <span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Dict-PED'>PED</span>: “<span lang='pi'>Rūpa</span>: form, figure, appearance, principle of form, etc.”</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "16",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>DN&#8239;33<span class='scsegments'>:1.10.75–1.10.76</span></span> <span class='ptsref'>PTS: D III 217</span> <span lang='pi'>Tivi&shy;dhena</span> <span lang='pi'>rū&shy;pa&shy;saṅ&shy;ga&shy;ho</span>: <span lang='pi'>san&shy;id&shy;as&shy;sa&shy;na&shy;sap&shy;paṭi&shy;ghaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>rūpaṁ</span>, <span lang='pi'>ani&shy;das&shy;sana&shy;sap&shy;paṭi&shy;ghaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>rūpaṁ</span>, <span lang='pi'>ani&shy;das&shy;sanāp&shy;paṭi&shy;ghaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>rūpaṁ</span>, “The threefold classification of form: visible tangible form, invisible tangible form, and invisible intangible form.”</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "17",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>MN&#8239;21<span class='scsegments'>:14.1–14.10</span></span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "18",
    "fnHTML": "<p>Cf. <span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Analayo 2017a'>Anālayo 2017</span> p.13: “This [<span lang='pi'>ani&shy;das&shy;sana</span>] also occurs in a description of space, which is said to be immaterial, <span lang='pi'>arūpa</span>, and invisible, <span lang='pi'>ani&shy;das&shy;sana</span>, a context where the two terms seem to function as near synonyms.”</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "19",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Warder 1991a'>Warder</span> p.354</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "20",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>AN&#8239;9.34<span class='scsegments'>:6.1–6.2</span></span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "21",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;1.27<span class='scsegments'>:2.1–2.2</span></span> &amp; <span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;1.10<span class='scsegments'>:14.1–14.2</span></span>. The Chinese parallels of <span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;1.27</span> (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sa601' class='extlink'>SĀ 601</a> and <a href='https://suttacentral.net/sa-2.176' class='extlink'>SĀ-2 176</a>) appear not to have “where earth, water, fire, and air find no footing”. Cf. <span class='sesame' data-sesame-key='zotref:Sujato 2011b'>Sujato 2011b</span>.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "22",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;8.1<span class='scsegments'>:3.1–3.4</span></span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "23",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;1.27<span class='scsegments'>:2.5–2.6</span></span> mentions the cessation of <span lang='pi'>nā&shy;ma&shy;rū&shy;pa</span>. In <span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;1.10<span class='scsegments'>:12.3–15.4</span></span> the verses were spoken when monks asked about the faith of the arahant Bāhiya who just passed away. <span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;8.1</span> mentions the absence of all form and the formless. All other factors in this inspired utterance describe the end of rebirth from different perspectives. So all three texts are about nibbāna after death.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "24",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>MN&#8239;98<span class='scsegments'>:11.55–11.58</span></span> <span class='ptsref'>PTS: M II 121</span> &amp; <span class='sclinktext'>Dhp&#8239;409</span></p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "25",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span lang='pi'>viñ&shy;ñā&shy;ṇa&shy;ni&shy;ro&shy;dhā</span> <span lang='pi'>nā&shy;ma&shy;rū&shy;pa&shy;ni&shy;rod&shy;ho</span> in e.g. <span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;12.1<span class='scsegments'>:3.3</span></span>.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "26",
    "fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>Snp&#8239;5.2<span class='scsegments'>:6.3–6.6</span></span>: <span lang='pi'>yattha</span> <span lang='pi'>nāmañca</span> <span lang='pi'>rūpañca</span>, <span lang='pi'>asesaṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>up&shy;ar&shy;uj&shy;jha&shy;ti</span>; <span lang='pi'>viñ&shy;ñā&shy;ṇas&shy;sa</span> <span lang='pi'>ni&shy;ro&shy;dhe&shy;na</span>, <span lang='pi'>et&shy;thet&shy;aṁ</span> <span lang='pi'>up&shy;ar&shy;uj&shy;jha&shy;ti</span>.</p>"
  },
  {
    "fnNumber": "27",
